				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$(f_1 (x), f_2 (x),...,f_n (x))$$\end{document}(f1(x),f2(x),...,fn(x)) on the training data. The outputs, combined with the original feature set, become the input for the next layer. Meta-Model A strong performing model like in this case XGBoost is used as the meta-model to fit the best predictors. It derives the final leads based on the patterns of intermediate outputs of the base models. XGBoost was chosen due to its ability to deal with overfitting and its high performance on tabular datasets.

